  <!-- ═══ WHAT THE MODEL DOESN'T CAPTURE ═══ -->
  <h2>What This Model Doesn't Capture</h2>
  <p>No model is complete. Here's what a DCF inherently misses for an alternative asset manager.</p>

  <h3>Upside risks (our number could be too low)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Global Atlantic:</strong> KKR's acquisition of the remaining stake in Global Atlantic gives them a massive, permanent capital base to drive fee-related earnings. If synergies exceed expectations, our growth rate is too low.</li>
    <li><strong>Retail Democratization:</strong> If KKR successfully taps into the multi-trillion-dollar high-net-worth individual market (which is vastly under-allocated to alternatives), AUM growth could accelerate.</li>
    <li><strong>Performance Fee Super-Cycle:</strong> If equity markets remain incredibly strong, KKR could see a cascade of massive realizations, pulling forward billions in cash flow.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Downside risks (our number could be too high)</h3>
  <ul>
    <li><strong>Prolonged Deal Drought:</strong> If M&A and IPO markets freeze due to high interest rates or recession, realizations drop to zero, devastating near-term cash flows.</li>
    <li><strong>Regulatory Scrutiny:</strong> Private credit and private equity are facing increased scrutiny from the SEC and global regulators, potentially increasing compliance costs or capping fees.</li>
    <li><strong>Balance Sheet Risk:</strong> Unlike asset-light peers, KKR invests heavily off its own balance sheet. In a severe downturn, mark-to-market losses on its debt pile could be severe.</li>
  </ul>

  <!-- ═══ FAQ ═══ -->
  <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="faq">
    <details>
      <summary>Why is KKR's Net Debt so high?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">Unlike traditional asset managers, KKR has a "capital markets" business and invests heavily alongside its clients using its own balance sheet. They issue debt to fund these investments. While it looks scary, much of this is non-recourse or backed by specific, cash-flowing assets.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why normalize Free Cash Flow instead of using GAAP?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">A private equity firm's cash flow comes in two forms: steady management fees and lumpy performance fees (carried interest). If you do a DCF using a peak year (like 2024 at $6.5B) you will vastly overvalue the company. If you use a trough year (like 2023 at -$1.6B) the math breaks. Normalizing smooths the cycle.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Why use a 10.5% discount rate?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">KKR is inherently a leveraged play on global economic growth (Beta > 2.0). The high beta demands a higher cost of equity. While their management fees are stable, their performance fees are highly correlated to market booms and busts. 10.5% adequately compensates for this volatility.</div>
    </details>
    <details>
      <summary>Is this a buy recommendation?</summary>
      <div class="faq-answer">No. This is an analytical framework for estimating intrinsic value. Whether to buy depends on your personal risk tolerance, portfolio allocation, time horizon, tax situation, and conviction in the assumptions. We provide the tools and transparency — you make the decision.</div>
    </details>
  </div>

